Definitely Maybe (Russian: &lt;U+0417&gt;&lt;U+0430&gt; &lt;U+043C&gt;&lt;U+0438&gt;&lt;U+043B&gt;&lt;U+043B&gt;&lt;U+0438&gt;&lt;U+0430&gt;&lt;U+0440&gt;&lt;U+0434&gt; &lt;U+043B&gt;&lt;U+0435&gt;&lt;U+0442&gt; &lt;U+0434&gt;&lt;U+043E&gt; &lt;U+043A&gt;&lt;U+043E&gt;&lt;U+043D&gt;&lt;U+0446&gt;&lt;U+0430&gt; &lt;U+0441&gt;&lt;U+0432&gt;&lt;U+0435&gt;&lt;U+0442&gt;&lt;U+0430&gt;, Za milliard let do konza sveta, literal translation: One billion years before the end of the world) is a sci fi novel written in 1976 by Arkady and Boris Strugatsky. Noel Gallagher saw the promo ad in a pub and decided to name his band's, called Oasis, first album after the novel.
Plot summary
Dmitri Malyanov is a young astronomer, working on stellar astronomy. As he tries to resolve his equations, he feels that he is on the edge of a revolutionnary discovery.
But as he approaches the solution, strange phenomena start occurring all around him, preventing him from finishing his work: telephone ringing all the time, a beautiful girl claiming to be his wife's friend appearing on his doorstep and so on. Coincidence? Malyanov's friends, also researchers experimenting similar disturbances, don't think so...
